    <stitle>CAM AIR FOUNDATION BRAKES - DISASSEMBLY - BRAKE GROUPS WITH SPIDERS</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="disassemble" graphiccount="10">
        <title>BRAKE GROUPS WITH SPIDERS</title>
        <svcprocinfo>
            <para>Three basic variations will be found in brake groups which use spiders.</para>
            <seqlist style="arabic">
                <item>
                    <para>Eaton brake groups (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0400506">Figure 6</hotlnk>) use a fixed anchor pin with open end shoes at
                        anchor end.
                    </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Rockwell "P" Series brake groups (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0400507">Figure 7</hotlnk>) have removable anchor pins which utilize brake
                        shoes with closed anchor pin openings (holes).
                    </para>
                </item>
                <item>
                    <para>Rockwell "Q" Series brake groups (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0400508">Figure 8</hotlnk>) have removable anchor pins with bushing and open
                        end anchor location on brake shoes.
                    </para>
                </item>
            </seqlist>
            <figure id="f0400506" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0400506" filename="../figg04/G0400506.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 6. Eaton Brake with Spider and Fixed Anchor Pins</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. SPIDER</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. LINING AND SHOE</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. ROLLERS</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. CAM</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. RETURN SPRING</callout1>
                    <callout1>6. RETAINER SPRING</callout1>
                    <callout1>7. ANCHOR PIN</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0400507" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0400507" filename="../figg04/G0400507.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 7. Rockwell "P" Series Brake with Spider</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. SPIDER</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. LINING AND SHOE</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. LOCK SCREWS</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. LOCK WIRE</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. ANCHOR PIN</callout1>
                    <callout1>6. LOCK RING AND WASHER ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                    <callout1>7. RETURN SPRING</callout1>
                    <callout1>8. ROLLERS</callout1>
                    <callout1>9. CAM</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0400508" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0400508" filename="../figg04/G0400508.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 8. Brake Spider With Removable Anchor Pins</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. ANCHOR PIN</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. LOCK BOLT</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. SPIDER</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
        </svcprocinfo>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Eaton Brake (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0400506">Figure 6</hotlnk>)
            </title>
            <para>Remove brake shoes as follows.</para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove brake dust shields.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Using a suitable pry bar, pry each shoe (one at a time) away from the cam and lift out
                    the rollers and retainers.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">With the rollers removed, the shoe return spring will be loose and can be slipped off
                    the links between the shoe webs.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">The lower shoe will hang down. Remove the lower shoe from anchor pin retaining
                    springs.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the upper shoe and the two retaining springs.</para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>When removing the automatic slack adjuster, refer to GROUP 04 - BRAKES in the CTS-5000 Master
                        Service Manual.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">With manual slack adjusters, mark the position of the slack adjuster in relation to the
                    camshaft.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Disconnect the clevis pin connecting the brake chamber push rod to the slack adjuster.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the lock ring retaining the slack adjuster to the end of the cam shaft. Note
                    location of spacer washers for reassembly purposes.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove slack adjuster from camshaft.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove camshaft from spider and camshaft bracket.</para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Rockwell "P" Series Brake (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0400507">Figure 7</hotlnk>)
            </title>
            <para>Remove brake shoes as follows.</para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove brake dust shields.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">With a suitable bar, pry each shoe one at a time away from the cam and lift roller
                    assemblies from end of shoes.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">After the rollers are removed, the shoe return spring will be loose and can be slipped
                    off the links between the shoe webs.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove anchor pin retainers (lock rings), seal retainers and felt seals.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Cut lock wire and remove anchor pin lock bolt (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0400508">Figure 8</hotlnk>). The anchor pin can then be removed. As pins are forced
                    out, the shoes will be free. Remove shoes.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>When removing the automatic slack adjuster, refer to GROUP 04 - BRAKES in the CTS-5000 Master
                        Service Manual.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">With manual slack adjusters, mark position of slack adjuster in relation to camshaft.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove clevis pin connecting brake chamber push rod to slack adjuster.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove lock ring retaining slack adjuster to end of camshaft. Note location of spacer
                    washers for reassembly purposes.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove slack adjuster from camshaft.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Push or tap camshaft from spider and camshaft bracket.</para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Rockwell "Q" Series Brake (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f0400509">Figure 9</hotlnk>)
            </title>
            <figure id="f0400509" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0400509" filename="../figg04/G0400509.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 9. Rockwell "Q" Series Brake With Spider and Removable Anchor Pins</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. SPIDER</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. LINING AND SHOE</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. ROLLERS</callout1>
                    <callout1>4. ROLLER RETAINERS</callout1>
                    <callout1>5. CAM</callout1>
                    <callout1>6. RETURN SPRING</callout1>
                    <callout1>7. ANCHOR PINS</callout1>
                    <callout1>8. RETAINER SPRING</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <para>Remove brake shoes as follows.</para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Disconnect lower and upper cam roller retainers (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0400510">Figure 10</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0400510" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0400510" filename="../figg04/G0400510.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="272px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 10. Disconnecting Roller Retainers</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Press down on lower brake shoe and remove lower cam roller assembly (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0400511">Figure 11</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0400511" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0400511" filename="../figg04/G0400511.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="272px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 11. Removing Lower Cam Roller</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Lift upper shoe and remove remaining roller assembly (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0400512">Figure 12</hotlnk>)
                </para>
                <figure id="f0400512" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0400512" filename="../figg04/G0400512.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="272px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 12. Removing Upper Cam Roller</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">After removing roller assemblies, the shoe return spring will be loose and can be
                    slipped from the links between shoe webs (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0400513">Figure 13</hotlnk>)
                </para>
                <figure id="f0400513" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0400513" filename="../figg04/G0400513.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="272px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 13. Remove Shoe Return Spring</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Swing lower shoe back about 180 degrees to release the spring tension on the retainer
                    springs (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0400514">Figure 14</hotlnk>). Remove outer retainer spring (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0400515">Figure 15</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0400514" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0400514" filename="../figg04/G0400514.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="272px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 14. Rotate Lower Shoe Approximately 180&#176;</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="f0400515" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0400515" filename="../figg04/G0400515.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1"
                             scalefitwidth="248px" scalefitheight="272px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 15. Removing Retainer Springs</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove both shoes from the spider, then remove retainer spring from shoes.</para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>For vehicles with automatic slack adjusters, refer to GROUP 04 - BRAKES in the CTS-5000 Master
                        Service Manual.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Mark position of manual slack adjuster in relation to camshaft. Also note position of
                    adjusting screw.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove clevis pin connecting the brake chamber push rod to the slack adjuster.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove lock ring retaining slack adjuster to the end of camshaft.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove spacer, washer assembly, and slack adjuster from camshaft. Note location of
                    spacer washers for reassembly purposes.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Push or tap camshaft from spider and camshaft bracket.</para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
